👉 Problem: Lowest Common Ancestor in a BST (Leetcode 235)

✅ Key Idea
Use the BST property to locate the split point between p and q:
If both p and q are smaller than root → LCA lies in left subtree.
If both p and q are greater than root → LCA lies in right subtree.
Otherwise, the current root is the lowest node where they diverge, i.e., the LCA.

✨ Flashcard
"Both smaller → go left. Both bigger → go right. Otherwise → current root is the LCA."

⚡ Full Approach

Start from the root.
If p and q are both < root.val → move to root.left.
If p and q are both > root.val → move to root.right.
Otherwise → split point found → return root as LCA.

This works because in a BST:
Left subtree values < root.
Right subtree values > root.

⏱️ Complexity

Time: O(h), where h = height of the tree.
Worst case (skewed tree): O(n).
Best case (balanced tree): O(log n).
Space: O(1) (iterative, no recursion stack).

✅ Notes:

A recursive version works identically but uses O(h) space.
This only works for BSTs, not for arbitrary binary trees.

